Assignment 6¶

In this assignment, you'll analyze a collection of data sets from the San Francisco Open Data Portal and Zillow. The data sets have been stored in the SQLite database sf_data.sqlite, which you can download here. The database contains the following tables:

Table Description
crime Crime reports dating back to 2010.
mobile_food_locations List of all locations where mobile food vendors sell.
mobile_food_permits List of all mobile food vendor permits. More details here.
mobile_food_schedule Schedules for mobile food vendors.
noise Noise complaints dating back to August 2015.
parking List of all parking lots.
parks List of all parks.
schools List of all schools.
zillow Zillow rent and housing statistics dating back to 1996. More details here.

The mobile_food_ tables are explicitly connected through the locationid and permit columns. The other tables are not connected, but you may be able to connect them using dates, latitude/longitude, or postal codes.

Shapefiles for US postal codes are available here. These may be useful for converting latitude/longitude to postal codes.

Shapefiles for San Francisco Neighborhoods are available here.

Data munging : Integrating S.F. neighborhoods into our analysis¶

One of my interests in working with spatial data is trying to work with "areas" instead of points. Given that we have neighborhood shapefiles, I wanted to find the fascinating characteristics behind them. We have a very large dataset (crime) with many rows, but the points do not express which neighborhood each point is in. I decided to use Geopandas and do a point-in-plane with the spatial join operation. I use this extra information throughout my analysis.

Question 1: Which crime types are most common around San Francisco?

For the first question in exercise 1.2, I decided to find out which crimes were the most common by neighborhood. I knew I had to use some crafty SQL techniques to do this, so I decided to select the counts from a subtable that I created with some help from group by. I also had to invoke the max function, but if I did before selecting from the sub table, there may have been some issues.

In [13]:
common_crimes=pd.read_sql("SELECT name, Descript, max(count) AS count "
                          "FROM (SELECT name, Descript, count(name) AS count FROM crime2 GROUP BY name, Descript) "
                          "GROUP BY name",sf_data)

Before we take a visual examination of the data, let's how often each crime type apppeared as the maximum for each neighborhood:

Question 2: How do the arrest rates look across San Francisco? Which neighborhood has the highest percentage of arrests?

For this two-pronged question, I could answer it with a single set of data. Although I did have issues with trying to generate a fraction directly from the query, so I had to do two separate queries. The strategy behind the queries is to select the total number of crimes for each neighborhood, and then to also find the number of crimes where the resolution was a booked arrest. From this, we derive some fascinating results.

In [17]:
totals=pd.read_sql("SELECT name, sum(total) AS all_crime FROM (SELECT name, Resolution, count(name) AS total FROM crime2 "
            "GROUP BY Resolution, name) GROUP BY name",sf_data)
arrests=pd.read_sql("SELECT name, total AS arrests FROM (SELECT name, Resolution, count(name) AS total FROM crime2 "
            "GROUP BY Resolution, name) WHERE Resolution == 'ARREST, BOOKED' GROUP BY name",sf_data)
arrest_rates=totals.merge(arrests,on="name")
arrest_rates["arrest_rate"]=arrest_rates.arrests/arrest_rates.all_crime

We can start by checking the top 10 neighborhoods, to get an idea if the highest arrest neighborhood is much higher.

In [18]:

As we noticed from question 1, the Tenderloin district had a unique common crime. This might explain why it has such a high arrest rate. The issue from this analysis arises from the fact that the arrest rate is very dependent on crime, so the higher rates are probably explained by a presence of certain crimes happening. At the same time, the police department might also have an effect on the arrest rate or crime type.

Question 3: How good are the police departments at handling crimes in their own district? Are the police departments of San Francisco homogenous or heterogenous in their treatment of crime?

For the first part of question 3 I wanted to find a way to determine what neighborhoods are covered by each police district. I also wanted to measure how often the respective departments "cover" their own district, as in they don't get help from other districts. The strategy I'm using involves another invoking of the max function. I considered a neighborhood "covered" by a police district if the number of crime reports was highest with that district. I went through and used some geopandas techniques that involved "buffering" and "cascading" to combine neighborhood polygons. The plot result is below after the code.

How well do the respective police departments handle cases in their own districts?

In [20]:
#Generate a SQL query that does the following: determine the police department that serves the neighborhood
districts=pd.read_sql("SELECT name, PdDistrict, max(total) AS dept_cases, sum(total) AS total_cases "
            "FROM (SELECT PdDistrict, name, count(name) "
            "AS total FROM crime2 GROUP BY PdDistrict, name ORDER BY name) GROUP BY name",sf_data)
#Aggregate the data frame into districts with dissolve and only keep district and geometry
sfpd_df=sf_neighborhoods.merge(districts,how="outer",on="name").dissolve(by="PdDistrict")
sfpd_df=sfpd_df.reset_index().rename(columns={"index":"PdDistrict"}).iloc[:,0:2]
sfpd_df.geometry=gpd.GeoSeries([shapely.ops.cascaded_union(district.buffer(.0001)) for district in sfpd_df.geometry])
#Unfortunately geopandas cannot properly do numerical aggregation, so I had to invoke pandas here
district_cases=sf_neighborhoods.merge(districts,how="outer",on="name").groupby("PdDistrict").sum().reset_index()
sfpd_df=sfpd_df.merge(district_cases,on="PdDistrict")
sfpd_df["case_rate"]=sfpd_df.dept_cases/sfpd_df.total_cases
In [21]:
sfpd_df['coords'] = sfpd_df['geometry'].apply(lambda x: x.representative_point().coords[:])
sfpd_df['coords'] = [coords[0] for coords in sfpd_df['coords']]
sfpd_df.plot(column="case_rate",cmap="RdYlGn")
for idx, row in sfpd_df.iterrows():
    plt.annotate(s=row['PdDistrict'], xy=row['coords'],
                 horizontalalignment='center')
plt.title("Case handling rate by police district in San Francisco")
plt.show()

It appears that the residential districts, covered by Taraval and Ingleside are much more likely to handle their own cases. Another obvious factor that appears to be affecting the coverage rate is how large the district is itself, and how many bordering districts it has.

Which crimes receive more heterogenous discipline? The next question involves doing some statistical analysis. I wanted to measure the dependence of crime given that it occurs in a given police district. I decided to use Pearson's Chi-sqaured statistic. Although the statistic cannot determine which district is causing the dependence, we can use it as a way to find interesting crime treatments in San Francisco. The plot result is at the end of the code.

In [22]:
#Create a generalized query function to get Pearson's chi-squared for the top 20 crime descriptions
def findChisq(description):
    crimetable=pd.read_sql("SELECT PdDistrict, Resolution, count(PdDistrict) AS numcrimes FROM crime2 WHERE Resolution IN('ARREST, BOOKED', " 
            "'NONE') AND Descript=='"+description+"' GROUP BY PdDistrict, Resolution",sf_data)
    chi2,p,dof,ex=scipy.stats.chi2_contingency(crimetable.pivot(values="numcrimes",index="PdDistrict",columns="Resolution"),correction=True)
    return([description,chi2,p])

common_descs=pd.read_sql("SELECT Descript, count(Descript) FROM crime2 GROUP BY Descript ORDER BY count(Descript) DESC LIMIT 20",sf_data)

chisq_crimes=[findChisq(d) for d in common_descs.Descript]
chisq_crime_df=pd.DataFrame(np.array(chisq_crimes),columns=["crime","chisq","pvalue"])
chisq_crime_df["chisq"]=np.array(chisq_crime_df.chisq,dtype="float")

chisort=chisq_crime_df.sort_values(by="chisq",ascending=False)
chisort.chisq.plot(kind="bar")
plt.xticks(list(range(len(chisort))), chisort.crime, rotation=90, fontsize = 12)
plt.ylabel("Chi-squared value")
plt.title("Using Pearson's chi-squared to determine heterogenous crimes by police department")
plt.show()

We have discovered that shoplifting and vandalism are highly dependent by department. This result is a very fascinating outlier and we will use it for question 4.

Analysis: It appears that the police departments are extremely heterogenous in their treatment of shoplifting and vandalism. We will explore which departments differ in treatment in question 3.

Question 4: Which police departments are 'tough' and 'soft' on shoplifting and vandalism? Are there different patterns for arrest rates for certain crimes?

For the fourth question, I decided to dig deeper into our result from question 3. I wanted to derive further characteristics about the police departments, so I decided to examine which departments were causing the chi-square outlier results, plus more. I started off by generating a function that gets the arrest rates for a given crime description. The plot result delivers us an answer to the massive chi squared values.

In [23]:
def getProportions(crime):
    crime_counts=pd.read_sql("SELECT PdDistrict, Resolution, count(PdDistrict) AS numcrimes FROM crime2 WHERE Resolution IN('ARREST, BOOKED', " 
            "'NONE') AND Descript=='"+crime+"' GROUP BY PdDistrict, Resolution",sf_data)
    totals=crime_counts.groupby("PdDistrict").numcrimes.apply(sum,axis=0).values
    crime_counts=crime_counts[crime_counts.Resolution=="ARREST, BOOKED"]
    crime_counts["arrest_rate"]=crime_counts.numcrimes.values/totals
    crime_counts=crime_counts.drop(["numcrimes","Resolution"],1)
    crime_count_df=sfpd_df.merge(crime_counts,on="PdDistrict")
    return(crime_count_df)

Finding crimes that departments "over" arrest at:

For the second part of the question, I decided to find characteristics about departments that were not the Tenderloin department. For the top 20 crime categories, I derived the rank a police department has for its arrest rate. I also derived a margin that measures the difference from the interdepartmental median arrest rate for each crime. I used these results to generate a table which shows the highest margin for each department.

In [26]:
def findRanks(crime_desc):
    crime_data=getProportions(crime_desc)
    crime_data["margin"]=crime_data.arrest_rate-np.median(crime_data.arrest_rate)
    crime_sort=crime_data.sort_values(by="arrest_rate")
    crime_sort["rank"]=crime_sort.reset_index().index.values+1
    crime_stats=crime_sort[["PdDistrict","arrest_rate","rank","margin"]]
    crime_stats.index=[crime_desc]*10
    return(crime_stats)

Question 5: Which neighborhoods are the most 'covered' by food trucks?

For my last question, I decided to examine something that was less about crime, and more lighthearted. I made use of food truck data to determine the locational spread of food trucks. I also wanted to demonstrate some fascinating geographic manipulation methods in geopandas. I decided to derive how much of the area of a neighborhood was "covered" by food trucks. Below is my result of the locations of food trucks, and their corresponding "radii".

In [37]:
food_locs=pd.read_sql("SELECT * FROM mobile_food_locations AS mfl INNER JOIN "
                      "mobile_food_schedule AS mfs ON mfl.locationid=mfs.locationid "
                      "INNER JOIN mobile_food_permits AS mfp ON mfs.permit=mfp.permit " 
                      "WHERE Latitude > 0 AND Longitude < 0 AND Status=='APPROVED'",sf_data)
food_xy=pd.read_sql("SELECT Longitude,Latitude FROM mobile_food_locations AS mfl INNER JOIN "
                      "mobile_food_schedule AS mfs ON mfl.locationid=mfs.locationid "
                      "INNER JOIN mobile_food_permits AS mfp ON mfs.permit=mfp.permit " 
                      "WHERE Latitude > 0 AND Longitude < 0 AND Status=='APPROVED' GROUP BY mfl.locationid",sf_data)
food_locs=food_locs.reset_index(drop=True)
